<br>
MICHAEL <br>
from FOOTFALL by Larry Niven &amp; Jerry Pournelle<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.up-ship.com/apr/michael.htm">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Science Fiction author Larry Niven needs no introduction. In his stories and collaborations, he has created some of the most imaginative and advanced spacecraft concepts ever conceived. Aldo Spadoni is an aerospace engineer and conceptual designer, specializing in the realistic design and visualization of future technology. Larry and Aldo have been collaborating to visually bring to life these wonderful spacecraft and other advanced technological concepts, as described in Larryís stories. The detailed designs are being developed by Aldo using aerospace industry systems engineering principles<br>
<br>
MICHAEL is an example of this endeavor. FOOTFALL by Larry Niven &amp; Jerry Pournelle is a classic story of alien invasion. The invading Fithp force the human race into a condition of servile surrender. In secrecy, humanity builds a battleship named MICHAEL, a nuclear powered mountain of steel to rise up into space and do battle with the aliens on their own turf. MICHAEL is based on the nuclear pulse propulsion concept developed under Project ORION (1958 ÅE1965). <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.up-ship.com/apr/images/Michael1a.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.up-ship.com/apr/images/Michael2a.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.up-ship.com/apr/images/Michael3a.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Incredible. Wasn't sure whether to put this here or in Science Fiction. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 10/13/02 10:13:10 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1220<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/14/02 8:48:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=167.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Ever wanted to see the Footfall Orion &quot;Michael&quot</span><hr size=1> That's pretty cool!  I always had trouble visualizing exactly how it looked... just one question, where are the massive shock absorbers?  Surely not the tiny things where the shuttles mount? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2250<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/15/02 12:21:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=167.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Ever wanted to see the Footfall Orion &quot;Michael&quot</span><hr size=1> Those look to be secondary shock absorbers. The central pillar appears to be the main compressor. The others appear to be more like stabilisers. <br>
<br>
Four shuttles and main boosters. Thats impressive. I don't think there actually were any shuttles at the time of writing Footfall. Shoot me down if I'm wrong. It's definately a futuristic design. Nothing retro about that baby. We should definately have something like that sitting someplace. Just in case we actually were attacked by hostile Aliens. Well, a hostile rock atleast. Even if it ended up never being used. Would make a fantastic guided tour for tourists.<br>
<br>
I originally created the Project Orion club to post my progress in forming a trust fund. So that the public could invest in such a venture. No nuclear material ofcourse. Just a working Super Orion minus fuel.<br>
<br>
&quot;Roll up. Roll up. See the Worlds only Starship.&quot; <br>
<br>
It might take 200 years or more to reach another Star but I think we could get away with the sales pitch. Setting up a legal trust fund in Australia proved prohibitively expensive though. It could be done in America. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 254<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/25/02 8:09:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=167.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Archangel Michael</span><hr size=1> I'd always wondered what the &quot;towers&quot; were. I'd thought the spurt bomb bays were inside part of the brick or main ship structure.<br>
<br>
 I could've sworn that the ship itself wasn't mentioned to have mounted the big 406mm guns; they were on the stovepipe auxilliary ships, while the guns mounted on Michael were smaller, like 127mm.<br>
<br>
I have doubts about those Battle Management Arrays and the thrust bomb magazines mounted on the towers directly on the plate.<br>
 It lessens the sprung mass (riding above the shocks) but submits the magazines and electronics to the shock directly.<br>
 It would seem to make sense to mount the BMA (Electronically steered planar radar for search/tracking/fire control direction) on the brick, protected from the shocks. We know some electronics can take much more shock than people, but your primary radar arrays?<br>
<br>
Frelling huge... No idea of the mass. I'll bend my brain trying to work it out in GURPS Vehicles rules...<br>
<br>
Edited:<br>
 More doubts about the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/ship/weaps/mk-7.htm">406mm guns</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (Always thought it was cheesy to have them in the book. Modern 203mm field guns are far more accurate &amp; versatile.): each 3 gun turret masses 1500 tons, with 50 crew... the powder is in bags, loaded separately from the shell. Though it's powerful, a missile magazine would be a better loadout.<br>
 The modern USN water cooled automatic naval guns are nice. The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/ship/weaps/mk-45.htm">127mm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is versatile, automatic (no crew in the turret above decks), and accurate. Some small <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.warships1.com/Weapons/WNIT_main.htm">naval guns</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (See esp the 3 and 4cm fast, compact mounts) may actually be better, with some as big as <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.warships1.com/Weapons/WNIT_4cm-70_Breda.htm">40mm twin</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> turrets being almost good enough to count as CIWS (robotic anti-missile mounts, certainly good enough for this, and you can carry a lot of them). <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0> at: 10/26/02 1:44:27 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=167.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=167.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=167.topic&index=3><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.emailToFriend?topicID=167.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.threadControl?topicID=167.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/space/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic 